    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName>Edinburgh</placeName>
                        <date>22<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> June 1881</date>
                        <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>Many thanks to you for your kind words of sympathy in regard to the movement in favour of poor Croll.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I am not very sanguine, but am resolven to leave no stone unturned to gain our end.</p>
                        <p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. George Darwin’s signature would have been most welcome. As you suppose, it will be best to obtain only a few signatures.</p>
                        <p>Yours very truly | Arch Geikie <lb/> <lb/></p>
                        <p rend="left">Charles Darwin Esqr</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>           
         
                       
         
                       
         
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD’s letter has not been found. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1127.xml">James Croll</ref> had been forced to retire early from the Geological Survey of Scotland in 1880 because of poor health. Geikie had drawn up a memorial to the prime minister, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1883.xml">William Ewart Gladstone</ref>, requesting an annuity from the civil list for Croll, to supplement his meagre Civil Service pension (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4102.xml">Irons 1896</ref>, pp. 363, 373).</note>
               
            </div>
            
        
            
